<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The starting situation</span>
<h2 class="h2">A DTC food brand with growth ambition and a $1M+ spend decision ahead</h2>
<p class="body"><strong>Company:</strong> Eat Clean — a DTC prepared-meal brand operating in the same broader category that Factor_ (acquired by HelloFresh) helped establish.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>The constraint:</strong> Multiple marketing channels in play, none operating at the efficiency the unit economics required. Email channel underperforming materially relative to channel benchmarks for DTC food. SEO strategy needed to be reconsidered in light of how AI-powered search (ChatGPT search, Perplexity, Google AI Overviews) was reshaping commercial-intent traffic patterns. A $1M+ growth-spend allocation decision pending, with no clear analytical foundation for where the next dollar should go.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>What Treetop was asked to own:</strong> Fractional CMO leadership. Holistic growth assessment across every marketing channel currently in play. Email lifecycle revamp as the highest-leverage immediate win. SEO strategy designed for both traditional search and the AI-search era. Competitor and marketplace assessment to inform the growth-spend allocation.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What we built</span>
<h2 class="h2">The first 90 days, then ongoing</h2>

<h3 class="h3">Email lifecycle revamp</h3>
<p class="body">The first high-leverage move. The pre-engagement email channel was producing ~$1.2K/month in net new acquisition revenue against a list size that should have produced 5-10× that. Diagnosis: lifecycle flows were generic batch sends rather than stage-segmented, creative was stale, and the offer architecture didn't tier appropriately to prospect intent signals.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Lifecycle stage segmentation rebuilt.</strong> Prospect cohorts separated by intent signal (browse abandon, cart abandon, post-first-purchase, churn-risk, win-back) with stage-appropriate creative and offer architecture.</li>
<li><strong>Creative refresh across all flows.</strong> New visual + copy treatment that matched the brand's positioning and the audience's voice.</li>
<li><strong>Result: 5× CTR lift.</strong> Net new monthly acquisition revenue from the email channel grew from $1.2K to $7.4K — over 6× lift on the acquisition number, driven primarily by the conversion + open-rate improvements compounding through the funnel.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Holistic growth-spend allocation framework</h3>
<p class="body">Eat Clean had a $1M+ pool of new growth capital to deploy and an unclear analytical basis for where it should go. The work: assess every channel currently in play (paid social, paid search, SEO, email, influencer, retention) on a unit-economics basis, model where incremental dollars produce the highest marginal return, and produce a recommended allocation that the team could actually execute against.</p>

<h3 class="h3">SEO strategy for the AI-search era</h3>
<p class="body">A core piece of the engagement: how does SEO strategy change when ChatGPT search, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews are reshaping commercial-intent traffic patterns? The work involved understanding which queries are most exposed to AI-search disintermediation, which queries remain traditional-search dominant, and how content strategy needs to adapt to capture commercial intent across both surfaces.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Commercial-intent query inventory.</strong> Mapped the queries that drive Eat Clean's existing traffic + the queries that should be driving traffic based on category demand.</li>
<li><strong>AI-search exposure analysis.</strong> Identified which queries are most likely to be answered directly by AI search (lower direct-traffic potential going forward) vs queries where direct site visits remain dominant.</li>
<li><strong>Content strategy adapted to both surfaces.</strong> Content built to perform well in both traditional Google rankings AND as cited sources in AI-search answers. Different page structures, different content depth, different schema markup.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Competitive marketplace assessment</h3>
<p class="body">Detailed competitive analysis across the DTC prepared-meal landscape: positioning gaps, creative patterns winning across the category, acquisition channel mix at scale, retention and lifecycle benchmarks. Used to inform pricing, brand positioning refinements, and the growth-spend allocation framework.</p>
</div></section>

